@book{Latash2008,
   abstract = {This chapter discusses the main problems of producing a purposeful motor action and those of control and coordination. To perform a voluntary movement, the central nervous system (CNS) has to formulate a motor task in terms of meaningful physical variables such as coordinates (trajectories) of important parts of the body, and forces that have to be produced against external objects. The processes involved in converting brain signals into actions are complex and poorly predictable. This is due to several factors such as: (1) Given a level of activation, muscle force depends on muscle length and velocity, (2) Muscle activation is defined by signals from descending pathways and reflex loops converging on the alpha-motoneurons, and (3) Signals along the reflex loops depend on various physical variables such as muscle length, velocity, force, pressure on the skin, joint capsule tension, as well as on signals from receptors in other muscles of the limb. The chapter highlights two approaches of motor learning. Motor learning does not lead to freezing or freeing of degrees of freedom. It leads to using all the original degrees of freedom to form an adequate space in which necessary synergies can be created, and then optimizing them with respect to important performance variables defined by the task.},
